Mobiles.LongDescription: The arena manager is here, selling tickets.
Mobiles.Description: The arena manager is a large, oafish looking man. His paunch makes youshudder, though he was one of the most celebrated gladiators of his time.He peers at you impatiently over the edge of his news journal, waitingfor you to buy a ticket.

Rooms.RoomDescription: You duck your head to avoid the heavy overhanging stone archway.Murals depicting legendary battles color the foreboding walls.  You seeflags of valor honoring heroes of history past and recent, visualincarnations of fairy tales swirling in your childhood remembrance.A large red leather book, adorned with colorful velvet illustrationsand gilded aged pages, lies open before you, urging you to ink your name.Dare you challenge the legends of Heroes old and new?

You are surrounded on all sides by large stone walls that loom overyour head. You attempt to move as silently as possible, settling your bootssoftly across the stone floors.  The heat from the spectators abovelingers upon you, making you uneasy and jittery despite your attemptsto master your environs.

Surrounding you always is the distant roar of the crowd.  Trying tobar this from your senses, you hunt your prey.  You inhale nothingbut the quiet humid dust rising from your stead.  Far removed fromthe civilized masses, the dark bloodstains smeared against the walldrive you forward to seek glory in your battle.

The pulse of the crowd follows you as you turn a slight cornerin the endless stone maze.  Timid ivy dares the incline of thefar wall, entangling grey stones and scattered debris from previousbattles. Straining your eye, you catch a faint etching near the coldground. Examining it closer, you find its simple message 'Honorbeyond death' strangely chilling.

You enter a quiet corner of the arena.  A laboriously designedmural has been erected here, detailing a battle between a strong,war humbled warrior and a five headed dragon.  The tales that canbe told about this hero are many, and already from the illustrationyou can discern remarkable triumphs brocaded around vicious tragedyin the furrow of his eyebrows.  His figure strong and bent, hisvisage shielded from cold desperation, he faces the Goddess of Truthin her mortal form, alone with a sword and a memory.A plaque, silent and humble:"Torquemada - a Hero well lived."

Surrounding you always is the distant roar of the crowd.  Trying tobar this from your senses, you hunt your prey.  You inhale nothingbut the quiet humid dust rising from your stead.  Far removed fromthe civilized masses, the dark bloodstains smeared against the walldrive you forward to seek glory in your battle.

The light dims a bit here, for you have entered a room fertile withvines, brazen with negligence, lazily scaling the stone slabs.They weave their way against the wall, and spiral above it mimicingthe most tranquil of bridal gazebos.  The vines shelter you from thedin of the spectators, much to your pleasure, for their sport has notyet ceased to annoy you.

Rooms.RoomName: A Passageway in the Arena of Legends
Rooms.RoomDescription: This hallway is a welcome break from the solid stone you havebeen treading.  Wary, you manuever this stretch with the greatestagility and caution.

Surrounding you always is the distant roar of the crowd.  Trying tobar this from your senses, you hunt your prey.  You inhale nothingbut the quiet humid dust rising from your stead.  Far removed fromthe civilized masses, the dark bloodstains smeared against the walldrive you forward to seek glory in your battle.

Surrounding you always is the distant roar of the crowd.  Trying tobar this from your senses, you hunt your prey.  You inhale nothingbut the quiet humid dust rising from your stead.  Far removed fromthe civilized masses, the dark bloodstains smeared against the walldrive you forward to seek glory in your battle.

Scores of would be heroes have rushed through these hallways,each seeking redemption, gold, or for his story to be echoed inthe legends of generations to come who will sit by campfires,reading their dreams in the night sky.  You grip your weaponmore tightly in the vision of countless names engraved into thisroom's walls, each one having sought victory only to sink backinto obscurity, bodies fallen into the dirt of the cold stone floor.

Surrounding you always is the distant roar of the crowd.  Trying tobar this from your senses, you hunt your prey.  You inhale nothingbut the quiet humid dust rising from your stead.  Far removed fromthe civilized masses, the dark bloodstains smeared against the walldrive you forward to seek glory in your battle.

Carressing the walls, you enter so as to render your crookedshadow as inconspicuous as possible for you know not if yourprey lays in wait just outside the reach of your eye.A discoloring of the ground several yards ahead of you breaksthe monotony of the grey stone slabs, and you move forward toexamine the waste of charcoal beneath your feet.  Rubbing yourtoe along the black circle extends dark lines from the bordersof the charcoal circle.  Wonderingly, you remember whispered storiesof magic users, when trapped into certain death by their foes,would seek escape to the madness of oblivion and instead burnthemselves alive in sacrifice to their art.

Surrounding you always is the distant roar of the crowd.  Trying tobar this from your senses, you hunt your prey.  You inhale nothingbut the quiet humid dust rising from your stead.  Far removed fromthe civilized masses, the dark bloodstains smeared against the walldrive you forward to seek glory in your battle.

The battle already commenced, your forehead involuntarily breaksout in cold sweat.  You assess the room before you, sensingthat your opponent has not yet tread this path.  The shadow ofa cloud passing over a pale sky startles you, and the sterilebattleground does nothing to soothe your tense muscles.Shield raised protectively, you move forward to claim the gloryat stake.

You climb two wide flight of stairs, where the doorway opensto an open sky overlooking a stone maze of intersecting rooms.The room before you is split in half, with both sides facing thecenter of the arena, and a small aisleway to traverse the dissectingseating arrangements.  The aisles on both sides reach crookedlyinto the sky, forming a dome above the combatants you are to witnessbelow.  If hefty bouncers aren't enough to discourage misbehavior,a shield of magic prevents you from interfering with the duel in any way.
